{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491512"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:50:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:50:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"965"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/965"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.51,0.07,0.29,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"965"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53589"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/965"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"965"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39045"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7660"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42185"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53589"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents with a one-week history of colicky abdominal pain and recent onset of a rash, mainly on his legs and feet (Image). His abdominal pain is aggravated with meals and associated with bloody diarrhoea. He presented two weeks earlier to his general practitioner with a sore throat and a swollen tender left ankle and was given a course of antibiotics and antipyretics. On examination his blood pressure is 166/90 mmHg, pulse 88/min, temperature 37.8\u00b0C, respiratory rate 24/min and oxygen saturation 98% on room air. Apart from the rash, his abdomen is diffusely tender, soft with no guarding or rebound tenderness and bowel sounds are heard. Both ankles are swollen and tender. Investigations shows normal coagulation screen, platelet count 400x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (RR 150 - 400 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L), and erythrocyte sedimentation rate 31 mm/h (RR \u0026lt;10mm/h). Urine analysis reveals a trace of protein. Antistreptolysin O titre is elevated at 400 IU/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Crohn\u0027s disease","Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura","Meningococcaemia","Rheumatic fever","Varicella-zoster infection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with abdominal pain, arthritis and rash (palpable purpura with some haemorrhagic vesicles and some crusts). He gives history of a preceding upper respiratory tract infection. This presentation is suggestive of\u003Cstrong\u003E Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura \u003C/strong\u003E(HSP).  Whilst the 75 - 90% of cases are in children, this can also be a disease of adults which must be considered for potential affects on the renal system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHSP is a small vessel vasculitis in which immune complexes of IgA and complement component 3 (c3) are deposited on capillaries, venules and arterioles. Exposure to an antigen from an infection, medication, or other environmental factor may trigger antibody and immune complex formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the EULAR/PRINTO/PRES criteria, the diagnosis of HSP is based on:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMandatory criterion: purpura or petechiae with lower limb predominance\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMinimum one out of four criteria\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiffuse abdominal pain with acute onset\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHistopathology showing leukocytoclastic vasculitis or proliferative glomerulo-nephritis, with predominant IgA deposits\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArthritis or arthralgia of acute onset\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal involvement in the form of proteinuria or haematuria\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn\u003Cstrong\u003E Crohn\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E, abdominal pain, diarrhoea, and weight loss are the usual presenting features. Extraintestinal manifestations may include arthritis and skin lesions. However, the short duration and the presence or renal involvement makes HSP more likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningococcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E may manifest with fever, purpuric rash and arthritis. These symptoms may overlap and occasionally be confused with those of HSP. However, patients with HSP are either afebrile or present with low-grade, rather transient, fever while in meningococcaemia fever is typically high. In addition, HSP abdominal pain and renal involvement are prominent features while in meningococcaemia CNS manifestations are expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatic fever\u003C/strong\u003E (RF) is an autoimmune disease associated with group A \u03b2-haemolytic streptococcal infection which may presents with fever and arthritis. RF diagnosis is based on modified Jones criteria with two major or one major and two minor criteria plus evidence of preceding Streptococcal infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMajor criteria: carditis (clinical and/or subclinical), arthritis (polyarthritis), chorea, Erythema marginatum, and subcutaneous nodules\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMinor criteria: olyarthralgia, fever (\u226538.5\u00b0 F), sedimentation rate \u226560 mm and/or C-reactive protein (CRP) \u22653.0 mg/dl, and prolonged PR interval (unless carditis is a major criterion)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEvidence of preceding Streptococcal infection: Increased or rising anti-streptolysin O titer or A positive throat culture for group A \u03b2-haemolytic streptococci\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes zoster virus (HZV) infection\u003C/strong\u003E manifests as neuralgia followed by vesicular rash which usually affects a single dermatome in a unilateral band-like pattern. In addition, HZV infection would not explain other presenting features in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Henoch- Sch\u00f6nlein Purpura  (HSP)  belongs to leukocytoclastic  vasculitides, it is most often triggered by exposure to an exogenous antigen, typically an upper respiratory pathogen, immunization, or medication.","The classic triad of symptoms in HSP includes non-thrombocytopenic palpable purpura, arthritis, and colicky abdominal pain. Renal involvement, if present, is often mild but rarely may progress to chronic renal failure."],"references":["Roberts PF, Waller TA, Brinker TM, Riffe IZ, Sayre JW, Bratton RL. Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura: a review article. South Med J. 2007 Aug;100(8):821\u20134.","Ozen  S, Pistorio A, Iusan SM, et al. EULAR/PRINTO/PRES criteria for Henoch\u2013Sch\u00f6nlein purpura, childhood polyarteritis nodosa, childhood Wegener granulomatosis and childhood Takayasu arteritis: Ankara 2008. Part II: Final classification criteria Ann Rheum Dis 2010;69:798\u2013806","Jithpratuck W, Elshenawy Y, Saleh H, Youngberg G, Chi DS, Krishnaswamy G. The clinical implications of adult-onset henoch-schonelin purpura. Clin Mol Allergy. 2011 May 27;9(1):9  Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3125277/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39045"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"965"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18353"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18353"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e3282f3e-d013-4d16-93c2-ae6e2b344d9c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e3282f3e-d013-4d16-93c2-ae6e2b344d9c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39045"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-22T23:44:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-22T23:45:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"965"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53589"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","po